    1. http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/09/opinion/09lee.html?ex=1339041600&en=a2f3d8f1f3cfcb61&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss
    2. http://www.techliberation.com/archives/042141.php


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| The SoundExchange Billion Dollar Administrative Fee                |
|   from the crushing-greed dept.                                    |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday June 09, @14:31 (Music)               |
|   http://politics.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/09/1651202     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]palewook writes "On June 7th, Yahoo, RealNetworks, Pandora, and
Live365 sent letters to US lawmakers emphasizing they owe SoundExchange
[1]'administrative fees' of more than $1 billion dollars a year. These
fees would be paid for the 'privilege' of collecting the increased CRB
royalties effective July 15th, unless the [2]Internet Radio Equality Act
passes Congress. SoundExchange, the non-profit music industry entity,
admits the levied charge of $500 per 'channel' is supposed to only cover
their administrative costs. Last year, SoundExchange collected a total of
$20 million dollars from the Internet radio industry. Under the new
'administrative fee' RealNetworks, which hosted 400,000 unique subscribed
channels in 2006, would owe an annual administrative charge of 200
million dollars in addition to the retroactive 2006 rate hike per song
played."

Discuss this story at:
    http://politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/09/1651202

Links:
    0. http://surfdez.blogspot.com/
    1. http://news.com.com/8301-10784_3-9726943-7.html?part=rss&subj=news&tag=2547-1_3-0-20
    2. http://www.savenetradio.org/


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| "Puddles" of Water Sighted on Mars                                 |
|   from the interstellar-jackpot dept.                              |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday June 09, @15:22 (Space)               |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/09/1658223      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]eldavojohn writes "Further reinforcing the [1]theory of a wet Mars,
NewScientist is reporting on [2]what appear to be water puddles in newly
taken images from the Mars rover. While these results are controversial,
the assumption that these blue 'puddles' are water still has to be tested
by engineers. They'll try to measure the uniform smoothness of the puddle
surfaces. Analysis will also examine their apparent 'opaqueness', where
in some areas observers claim to see pebbles underneath the surface of
the blue areas. From the article: 'No signs of liquid water have been
observed directly from cameras on the surface before. Reports last year
pointed to the existence of gullies on crater walls where water appears
to have flowed in the last few years, as shown in images taken from
orbit, but those are short-lived flows, which are thought to have frozen
over almost immediately.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/09/1658223

Links:
    0. http://ogami.subpop.com/
    1. http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/21/210208&tid=226
    2. http://space.newscientist.com/article/dn12026-mars-rover-finds-puddles-on-the-planets-surface.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| ISPs Starting To Charge for 'Guaranteed' Email Delivery            |
|   from the i-gare-on-tee dept.                                     |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday June 09, @16:26 (The Internet)        |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/09/199259               |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Presto Vivace writes "Under the guise of fighting spam, five of the
largest Internet service providers in the U.S. plan to start charging
businesses for [0]guaranteed delivery of their e-mails. In other words,
with regular service we may or may not deliver your email. If you want it
delivered, you will have to pay deluxe. 'According to Goodmail, seven
U.S. ISPs now use CertifedEmail, accounting for 60 percent of the U.S.
population. Goodmail--which takes up to 50 percent of the revenue
generated by the plan--will for now approve only mail sent by companies
and organizations that have been operational for a year or more. Ordinary
users can still apply to be white-listed by individual ISPs, which
effectively provides the same trusted status.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/09/199259

Links:
    0. http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9588_22-6189298.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| China Censoring Flickr                                             |
|   from the you-get-no-flicks dept.                                 |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday June 09, @17:37 (Censorship)          |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/09/1914226          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "It would appear that the Chinese government
is currently [0]censoring all photos on the site Flickr. A notice has
been posted in a Flickr help forum about this, but the service currently
doesn't have a fix for this. It would appear that China has turned on
their Golden Shield Project to censor the site. 'Jain Hua Li, a spokesman
for the Chinese Embassy in Washington, said he hadn't heard of Flickr
until told about it in a conversation with a Chronicle reporter, and then
suggested that the blocking may be because Chinese authorities are trying
to protect children from racy images. Lucie Morillon, the U.S.
representative for Reporters Without Borders, a French group that
promotes free expression, said that the Beijing government often censors
Web sites under the guise of protecting children or national security.
She called the blocking of Flickr "one more blow against the free flow of
information online by Chinese authorities" and added that it is
particularly lamentable in light of promises by China to loosen
restrictions before the 2008 Olympics in Beijing.' Thomas Hawk has a
[1]well-considered opinion to offer on this issue."

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/09/1914226

Links:
    0. http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/06/09/BUG9VQC8QE1.DTL
    1. http://thomashawk.com/2007/06/china-censors-flickr.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Attorney Sues Website Over His Online Rating                       |
|   from the don't-put-me-in-a-box dept.                             |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday June 09, @19:46 (The Courts)          |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/09/1922239          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "The Seattle Post-Intelligencer is reporting
that a local attorney is suing legal startup Avvo over a [0]rating that
was algorithmically assigned. The story covers the controversy of
computers grading humans. 'Browne, who has participated in a number of
high-profile cases in the state, including the defense of arsonist Martin
Pang, said in an interview that Avvo is being irresponsible with the
ratings and called them a fraud. And he questioned why Supreme Court
justices and prominent lawyers score so low. Three other attorneys
interviewed by the P-I also expressed doubts about the rating system,
while News.com reported that the site "seemed to be riddled with bizarre
errors."' Such practices are not new: the New York Times earlier this
year reported on Google [1]using algorithms to determine applicant
suitability. But what happens when you don't like the result? Can a
computer program be considered defamatory?"

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/09/1922239

Links:
    0. http://blog.seattlepi.nwsource.com/venture/archives/116417.asp#extended
    1. http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F06E7DA1730F930A35752C0A9619C8B63



